<br>
I've always believed that the Dark Elves learned it through their own dealings and experimentations.  I know that the Iksar learned all of the Arcane magics from old Shissar texts (Yes, they know Magery, Enchantry and Wizardry-those are just considered heretical arts by the Empire, and so are only practiced by the forsaken or in secret).  But the Tier'Dal, Trolls, Ogres, and Humans could just as easily have stumbled across it as they did the other schools of magic. <p><center><b>Kelisk Mae'Lokh</b></center><br><center>Chancellor of Skathris Ven'Sho--Patriarch of Cabilis</center><br><center><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=355953"><i>Inspect Kelisk?</i></a></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/utukka.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tukka</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 193<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/21/02 12:19:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2762.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.atlantic.net/~tukka/glowhand.jpg height=44 width=44></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I was the original poster</span><hr size=1> Kreelos makes a lot of good points, and its partially for these reasons that I don't think that Verant has built a really solid foundation on which for us to create characters to roleplay.<br>
<br>
Some very basic facts about the nature of Norrath's races and Norrath itself have been omitted.  In addition to the things he mentioned, there is nothing that I've read in any EQ history or lore that explains the nature of death in Norrath, and why and how people come back to life always after being slain, and how and why NPCs respawn, and how to reconcile the respawning of NPCs and PCs with historic deaths (like Ganak's death.)  Why do some people die and are never seen again, while others die and come back in a few minutes, while others die to be trapped in some other form (undead, ect.)<br>
<br>
If you want a look at a backstory that is coherant, consistent and well written, that does a good job (as far as I can tell, without having actually played the game) of covering all the bases, look at <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://shadowbane.ubisoft.com">Shadowbane</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br>
<br>
I think that on top of these missing facts, the static nature of the world does not help one bit either.  But a static world is okay, what I don't like is the fact that there are so many quests and named NPCs.  The way things are presented to you when you are doing a quest makes it sound like the quest has never been done before, and that when it is done, it shall never have to be done again, and in some cases quests are presented to you as if they will have some monumental, lasting significance.  Of course the reality is that this is not the case at all.  All of your deeds will wiped clean and forgotten within 20 minutes to 1 week of their having been done.<br>
<br>
To me, this is very non-conducive to the roleplay atmosphere of a game.  If makes me feel as if any interaction I have with the game environment and NPCs is pointless, and it promotes the mentality (even among roleplayers) that these quests and deeds are merely about the gameplay challenge of completing them and the reward (usually in the form of an item) you get for completing them.<br>
<br>
And I think that the way people treat and interact with the NPC representations of the &quot;game world&quot; will inevitably reflect on the way their interact with fellow players... as players rather than roleplayers or characters in a living world.<br>
<br>
With an effort, you can buck the trend, create your own backstory, overlook the lack of basic facts that you may have about your character's race, or the nature of the world itself and try to play around them, and roleplay... but for myself (and most others) it seems more effort than its worth.  Other games I have planed (<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.gemstone.net">GemStone III</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> for one) made it a lot easier for me to get into character and stay in character.<br>
<br>
This is the measure I use to determine whether or not the cohesiveness and continuity and details of a game's backstory is worth anything to a roleplayer.  The fact that histories and stories exist, even in volumes, does not matter.  It doesn't even matter if those stories are very interesting to read.  What matters is how conducive the world is to roleplaying, and whether or not it encourages it, and makes it easy for someone who isn't a diehard roleplayer or someone who is new to roleplaying, because a diehard roleplayer can roleplay anywhere there's other roleplayers. <p><B><FONT FACE="Comic Sans MS">--Tukka</FONT></B><BR>
Player of <A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=189682">Velsor Secarne</A> (on Firiona Vie)
<BR>
Shadow Knight of Cazic-Thule<BR>
